# Generate 1 to 36 step ahead forecast for the prediction subsample, 2009Q1-2018Q4

# Multi-Step Forecast

m1.Mul.F <- forecast(m1, length(dlRPCE2))

plot(m1.Mul.F)

(c)

# Rolling Scheme Forecast

m1.Rol.F <- zoo()

fstQ <- 1955.25
lstQ <- 2008.75

for(i in 1:length(dlRPCE2)) {
  temp <- window(dlRPCE, start=fstQ + (i-1)/4, end = lstQ + (i-1)/4)
  m1.update <- arima(temp, order=c(3,0,2))
  m1.Rol.F <- c(m1.Rol.F, forecast(m1.update, 1)$mean)
 }
m1.Rol.F <- as.ts(m1.Rol.F)

plot(m1.Rol.F)

(d)

plot(m1.Mul.F, type="o", pch=20, xlim=c(1955,2017), ylim=c(-0.03,0.03),
     main = " Multi-step and Rolling Forecasts")
lines(m1.Mul.F$mean, type="p", pch=20, col="blue")
lines(m1.Rol.F, type="o", pch=20, col="red")
lines(dlRPCE, type="o", pch=20)

# Construct the transformed time series

TNPE <-
  tq_get("FRED/PAYNSA",
         get = "Quandl",
         from = "1975-01-01",
         to = "2018-12-01") %>%
  rename(E = value) %>%
  mutate(dE = E - lag(E),
         lE = log(E),
         dlE = lE - lag(lE),
         d12lE = lE - lag(lE, 12),
         dd12lE = d12lE - lag(d12lE))

# Plot ACF and PACF for lE, dlE, d12lE, dd12lE

maxlag <-60

par(mfrow=c(2,4))

Acf(TNPE$lE, type="correlation", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("ACF for log(E)")))
Acf(TNPE$dlE, type="correlation", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("ACF for ", Delta,"log(E)")))
Acf(TNPE$d12lE, type="correlation", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("ACF for ", Delta[12], "log(E)")))
Acf(TNPE$dd12lE, type="correlation", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("ACF for ", Delta, Delta[12], "log(E)")))

Acf(TNPE$lE, type="partial", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("PACF for log(E)")))
Acf(TNPE$dlE, type="partial", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("PACF for ", Delta, "log(E)")))
Acf(TNPE$d12lE, type="partial", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("PACF for ", Delta[12], "log( E)")))
Acf(TNPE$dd12lE, type="partial", lag.max = maxlag, ylab = "", main = expression(paste("PACF for ", Delta,Delta[12], "log(E)")))

The ACF for lE is decreasing. The ACF for dlE is alternating. The ACF for d12lE is decreasing and increasing again towards zero. The ACF for dd12lE is decreasing and alternating on the negative side. The PACF for lE, d12lE, and dd12lE has a similar shape that starts very high and stays close to the band in the end. Meanwhile, the PACF for dlE starts from within the band and exceeds beyond numerous times.

# Create a rolling scheme sequence of 1 period ahead forecasts for the prediction subsample 2015M1-2018M12 using the same model specification as in (f)

m5 <- arima(lE1, order=c(1,2,1), seasonal=list(order=c(2,1,1), period = 12))

end <- 2014 

forecasting.length <- window(lE, start = end + (1/12))

m5.f.h <- forecast(m5, length(forecasting.length))

autoplot(m5.f.h)

lE2 <-window(lE, start=2015, end = 2017, frequency=12)

m5.Rol.F <- zoo()

fstQ <- 1975

lstQ <- 2014

for(i in 1:length(lE2)) {
  temp <- window(lE, start=fstQ + (i-1)/12, end = lstQ + (i-1)/12)
  m5.update <- arima(temp, order = c(1,2,1), seasonal = list(order = c(2,1,1), period = 12))
  m5.Rol.F <- c(m5.Rol.F, forecast(m5.update, 1)$mean)
}

m5.Rol.F <- as.ts(m5.Rol.F)

plot(m5.Rol.F)

Question 3

# Obtain the two following time series: labor productivity and total hours worked

lpo<-Quandl("FRED/OPHNFB", type="zoo")
twho<-Quandl("FRED/HOANBS", type="zoo")

lp<-window(lpo,start="1947 Q1", end="2017 Q4")
twh<-window(twho,start="1947 Q1", end="2017 Q4")

(a)

# log of lp and twh

llp<-log(lp)*100
ltwh<-log(twh)*100

# first differences 
dllp<-diff(llp,1)
dltwh<-diff(ltwh,1)

par(mfrow=c(2,2))
plot(llp,xlab="Time", ylab="Log lp")
plot(ltwh,xlab="Time", ylab="Log twh")
plot(dllp,xlab="Time", ylab="First Diff Log lp")
plot(dltwh,xlab="Time", ylab="First Diff Log twh")

# ADF test of llp

adf.test(llp)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  llp
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.3352, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.4349
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# ADF test of ltwh

adf.test(ltwh)
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  ltwh
## Dickey-Fuller = -1.974, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.5871
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# ADF unit root test of dllp

adf.test(dllp)
## Warning in adf.test(dllp): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dllp
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.8656, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
# ADF unit root test of dltwh

adf.test(dltwh)
## Warning in adf.test(dltwh): p-value smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  dltwh
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.0531, Lag order = 6, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

It can be concluded that the log variables have a unit root. Meanwhile, since the p-value of the ADF unit root test for the first differences is less than 0.05, we can reject that there is a unit root for the first differences of the log of labor productivity (lp) and total hours worked (twh).

(b)

# Estimate a bivariate reduced form VAR using AIC information criteria to select number of lags

y<-na.trim(y)
y<-sweep(y,2,apply(y,2,mean))
VARselect(y,lag.max=8)
